        {
          "id": "math-14b4188d19d16c25",
          "front": "Simplify $\\dfrac{5+12i}{2-3i}$. Your answer should be of the form $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are both real numbers and written as improper fractions (if necessary).",
          "back": "Multiplying the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, we have \\begin{align*}\n\\dfrac{5+12i}{2-3i} \\cdot \\frac{2+3i}{2+3i} &= \\frac{5(2) + 5(3i) + 12i(2) +12i(3i)}{2(2) + 2(3i) + -3i(2) -3i(3i)}\\\\\n& = \\frac{-26+39i}{13} \\\\\n&= \\boxed{-2+3i}.\n\\end{align*}",
          "hint": "Category: Algebra, Difficulty: 5/5"
        },
        {
          "id": "math-3491201a6e5b5747",
          "front": "Solve for t: $3 \\cdot 3^t + \\sqrt{9 \\cdot 9^t} = 18$.",
          "back": "We note that $\\sqrt{9 \\cdot 9^t} = 3 \\cdot 3^t$. The equation becomes: \\begin{align*}\n3 \\cdot 3^t + 3 \\cdot 3^t &= 18\\\\\n\\Rightarrow 6 \\cdot 3^t &= 18 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow 3^t &= 3.\n\\end{align*}Therefore, $t = \\boxed{1}$.",
          "hint": "Category: Algebra, Difficulty: 3/5"
        },
        {
          "id": "math-0e524a323a4b6a43",
          "front": "Calculate $\\sqrt{\\sqrt[3]{0.000064}}$. Express your answer as a decimal to the nearest tenth.",
          "back": "We start by writing the decimal as a fraction, and we find \\begin{align*}\n\\sqrt{\\sqrt[3]{0.000064}} &= \\sqrt{\\sqrt[3]{\\frac{64}{10^6}}} = \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{2^6}{10^6}\\right)^{\\frac13}}\\\\\n&=\\sqrt{\\frac{2^{6\\cdot \\frac{1}{3}}}{10^{6\\cdot \\frac13}}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{2^2}{10^2}} = \\frac{2}{10} = \\boxed{0.2}.\n\\end{align*}",
          "hint": "Category: Algebra, Difficulty: 2/5"
        },
        {
          "id": "math-5808bd42d72df523",
          "front": "If $x = \\frac34$ and $y = \\frac43$ , find the value of $\\frac12x^6y^7$.",
          "back": "We have  \\[\\frac{1}{2} x^6 y^7 = \\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{3}{4}\\right)^6\\left(\\frac43\\right)^7 = \\frac{1}{2}\\cdot \\frac{3^6}{4^6} \\cdot \\frac{4^7}{3^7}\n=\\frac{1}{2} \\cdot\\frac{3^6}{3^7} \\cdot \\frac{4^7}{4^6} = \\frac{1}{2}\\cdot \\frac{1}{3} \\cdot 4 = \\boxed{\\frac{2}{3}}.\\]\n\nWe also could have tackled this problem quickly by noticing that if $x=\\frac34$ and $y=\\frac43$, then $xy=1$, so $\\frac{1}{2}x^6y^7 = \\frac{1}{2} (xy)^6y=\\frac{1}{2}\\cdot 1^6y = \\frac{1}{2}y = \\frac{2}{3}$.",
          "hint": "Category: Algebra, Difficulty: 2/5"
        }
