          "id": "math-eccb7e8f044f5caa",
          "front": "The center of the circle with equation $x^2+y^2=8x-6y-20$ is the point $(x,y)$. What is $x+y$?",
          "back": "We will complete the square to determine the standard form equation of the circle. Shifting all but the constant term from the RHS to the LHS, we have $x^2-8x+y^2+6y=-20$. Completing the square in $x$, we add $(-8/2)^2=16$ to both sides. Completing the square in $y$, we add $(6/2)^2=9$ to both sides. The equation becomes \\begin{align*}\nx^2-8x+y^2+6y&=-20\\\\\n\\Rightarrow x^2-8x+16+y^2+6y+9&=5\\\\\n\\Rightarrow (x-4)^2+(y+3)^2&=5\n\\end{align*} Thus, the center of the circle is at point $(4,-3)$ so $x+y=4+(-3)=\\boxed{1}$.",
          "hint": "Category: Algebra, Difficulty: 4/5"
