          "id": "math-c-158002a566b73dcf",
          "title": "If $a$ is a constant such that $4x^2 - 12x + a$ is the square of a binomial, then what is $a$?",
          "content": "**Problem (Algebra, Level 3):**\nIf $a$ is a constant such that $4x^2 - 12x + a$ is the square of a binomial, then what is $a$?\n\n**Solution:**\nIf $4x^2 - 12x + a$ is the square of a binomial, then the binomial has the form $2x+b$ for some number $b$, since $(2x)^2 = 4x^2$.  So, we compare $(2x+b)^2$ to $4x^2 - 12x + a$. Expanding $(2x+b)^2$ gives \\[(2x+b)^2 = 4x^2 + 4bx + b^2.\\]Equating the linear term of this to the linear term of $4x^2 - 12x+a$, we have $4bx=-12x$, so $b=-3$.  Thus, $a=b^2 = \\boxed{9}$.",
          "kind": "example"
