          "front": "For what value of $k$ does the line represented by the equation $-\\frac{1}{2}-2kx = 5y$ contain the point $\\left(\\frac{1}{4},-6\\right)$?",
          "back": "Since $\\left(\\frac{1}{4}, -6\\right)$ lies on the line, we plug $x = \\frac{1}{4}$ and $y = -6$ into the equation to get  \\begin{align*}\n-\\frac{1}{2} - \\frac{k}{2} &= 5(-6)\\\\\n\\Rightarrow\\qquad -1-k = -60\\\\\n\\Rightarrow\\qquad k=\\boxed{59}.\n\\end{align*}",
          "hint": "Category: Algebra, Difficulty: 4/5"
